Midgaard's registry framework creates persistent ambiguity for Monk practitioners. The Violet Compact's registry law requires formal documentation of practice, but the Inner and Deepest Forms' most important content is specifically resistant to external verification — a practitioner can perform the Outer Forms correctly while doing the Inner Forms incorrectly, and registry officials cannot distinguish the difference through standard credential assessment. Most Midgaard-based Monks operate under nominal registry compliance while maintaining that the registry's formal credential categories don't describe what Monk practitioners actually do. Guard Command's Ash-and-Iron Decades militarization found Monks to be efficient force multipliers — one trained Monk performing functions requiring multiple armed guards, with equipment independence making them easier to field in resource-constrained emergency situations. Guard Command veterans with Monk training are tracked under general unarmed practitioner categories rather than as a distinct credential type.

