Khenari sacred record practice and Monk tradition share a characteristic creating natural affinity: both maintain knowledge that is specifically resistant to external documentation in its most significant forms. Khenari death-rite knowledge includes practices transmitted through embodied lineage rather than written record, parallel to the Inner Forms' resistance to external verification. Khenari Monks in Midgaard tend to be more committed to the Inner and Deepest Forms' depth development than practitioners from other backgrounds. The Sealed Names Apparatus's attempts to create comprehensive registry documentation of Monk practice have found Khenari-tradition Monks the most consistent institutional resistors, on grounds that the registry's verification methodology cannot assess the actual practice it claims to document.

